{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595247"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:02:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:02:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15344"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15344"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0,0.1,0.03,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66473"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8035"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51925"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19520"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66473"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA parent brings their three-year-old child to the general practitioner with concerns about constipation that has been present for six months. The child has been resistant to toilet training.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a correct principle regarding childhood constipation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Functional constipation accounts for most cases","Abdominal X-rays should be performed routinely","Organic causes are found in most cases","Dietary changes alone usually resolve symptoms","Laxatives (aperients) should be avoided in children"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChildhood constipation is a common presentation to general practice in Australian. Childhood constipation is commonly caused by dietary factors such as insufficient fiber and fluid intake, as well as behavioral issues like withholding stool due to fear of pain or negative toilet experiences. Contributing factors can also include lack of physical activity, stress, and rarely, underlying medical conditions like hypothyroidism or coeliac disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EFunctional constipation\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for approximately 95% of cases in childhood constipation, with organic causes being rare. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely recommended for diagnosing constipation in children and should be reserved for specific clinical scenarios where there is diagnostic uncertainty. The diagnosis is primarily clinical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrganic causes\u003C/strong\u003E such as Hirschsprung disease or anatomical abnormalities account for less than 5% of cases. \u003Cstrong\u003EDietary changes\u003C/strong\u003E alone are usually insufficient to treat established constipation and should be combined with other interventions. \u003Cstrong\u003ELaxatives (aperients)\u003C/strong\u003E are safe and effective in children when prescribed appropriately and are the key treatment of constipation in children.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Functional (idiopathic) constipation accounts for 95% of cases in children","Routine X-rays are not recommended for diagnosing constipation in children","Most cases of childhood constipation begin during toilet training"],"references":["Bolia R, Safe M, Southwell BR, King SK, Oliver MR. Paediatric constipation for general paediatricians: Review using a case-based and evidence-based approach. J Paediatr Child Health. 2020 Nov;56(11):1708-1718. doi: 10.1111/jpc.14720. PMID: 33197982.","Constipation in children and young people: diagnosis and management. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2017 Jul. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 99.) Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554924/","Pawasarat A, Biank VF. Constipation in Pediatrics: A Clinical Review. Pediatr Ann. 2021 Aug;50(8):e320-e324. doi: 10.3928/19382359-20210714-01. Epub 2021 Aug 1. PMID: 34398719."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51925"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51925"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T14:40:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T14:41:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66473"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi